WEBVTT

00:01.842 --> 00:09.850
♪♪

00:09.850 --> 00:17.818
♪♪

00:17.818 --> 00:25.826
♪♪

00:32.112 --> 00:38.078
♪♪

00:38.078 --> 00:40.521
[ Door closes ]

00:40.521 --> 00:49.369
♪♪

00:49.369 --> 00:58.218
♪♪

00:58.218 --> 01:07.067
♪♪

01:07.067 --> 01:09.309
[ Door opens ]

01:09.309 --> 01:13.994
[ Footsteps approaching ]

01:13.994 --> 01:15.956
[ Door unlocks ]

01:15.956 --> 01:23.283
♪♪

01:23.283 --> 01:31.772
♪♪

01:31.772 --> 01:33.854
[ Door unlocks ]

01:33.854 --> 01:40.981
♪♪

01:40.981 --> 01:42.543
[ Buzzer ]

01:42.543 --> 01:44.464
‐Sorry again to get you up
so early, Commander.

01:44.464 --> 01:47.267
‐Not a problem.
‐Right this way, Ms. Hagerty.

01:47.267 --> 01:48.989
I owe you one.

01:48.989 --> 01:54.635
♪♪

01:54.635 --> 01:56.837
Follow me this way,
Ms. Hagerty.

01:56.837 --> 02:03.243
♪♪

02:03.243 --> 02:06.527
‐I'm glad you called.
Thanks, Jeff.

02:06.527 --> 02:16.537
♪♪

02:16.537 --> 02:18.018
♪♪

02:18.018 --> 02:19.740
[ Door closes ]

02:19.740 --> 02:23.584
♪♪

02:23.584 --> 02:27.708
[ Boots thud ]

02:27.708 --> 02:31.592
♪♪

02:31.592 --> 02:33.594
[ Door opens ]

02:33.594 --> 02:42.923
♪♪

02:42.923 --> 02:52.252
♪♪

02:52.252 --> 02:54.334
‐Nick, I think if you hold
the blanket away with the claw

02:54.334 --> 02:56.216
while you're shoving
the cufflink through,

02:56.216 --> 02:58.018
it might settle down
that dynamic.

02:58.018 --> 03:00.781
‐Copy that.
Let's move in 10 centimeters.

03:00.781 --> 03:03.023
‐Tom, we're gonna need you
to come up.

03:03.023 --> 03:05.626
‐We're not finished.

03:05.626 --> 03:07.267
‐I'm aborting the sim.

03:09.069 --> 03:11.191
‐What's going on?

03:11.191 --> 03:12.953
‐I'll fly Matteo
out to cover your position.

03:12.953 --> 03:14.434
He could use the hours anyway.

03:14.434 --> 03:16.276
‐I hate disrupting training
like this.

03:16.276 --> 03:18.198
[ Bag zips ]
‐We got it covered.

03:18.198 --> 03:21.121
This doesn't have to be a repeat
of last time.

03:21.121 --> 03:23.764
Don't let that get
into your head.

03:23.764 --> 03:25.566
You just do what you need to do.

03:25.566 --> 03:28.128
‐[ Sighs ] Thanks.
‐Yeah.

03:30.851 --> 03:32.933
‐We'll do photos first?
‐Fine.

03:32.933 --> 03:36.056
‐You can start setting up
down here.

03:36.056 --> 03:37.377
Did you enjoy your flight?

03:37.377 --> 03:39.580
‐Yeah.
‐Very good. Glad to hear it.

03:42.262 --> 03:45.425
‐She's not in yet.
‐Is she on her way?

03:45.425 --> 03:47.628
‐Mr. Shultz, I'm Jason,
Laz's assistant.

03:47.628 --> 03:50.230
Please come with me.

03:50.230 --> 03:52.272
Got it.

03:52.272 --> 03:54.434
We're just gonna have to wait
in this conference room here,

03:54.434 --> 03:55.796
if you don't mind.
‐Okay.

03:55.796 --> 03:58.639
‐Jason told you?
‐You threw your back out.

03:58.639 --> 04:00.681
‐It's terrible luck.
I haven't put it out like this

04:00.681 --> 04:01.762
for a while.
[ Beeps ]

04:01.762 --> 04:03.483
‐I can come to you.

04:03.483 --> 04:05.245
‐Uh...

04:05.245 --> 04:08.168
perhaps we could postpone
till tomorrow.

04:08.168 --> 04:09.610
Jason could give you
a full tour,

04:09.610 --> 04:11.131
we could put you up
for the night.

04:11.131 --> 04:13.093
‐I have to be in Washington
tomorrow.

04:13.093 --> 04:16.977
Senator Mills, Thibodeaux, NASA.
It's a tight schedule.

04:16.977 --> 04:19.419
‐It's just I don't think
I can make it today, and I ‐‐

04:19.419 --> 04:21.421
I don't want you
to have to see me in bed.

04:21.421 --> 04:23.984
‐How about we can start
on the phone,

04:23.984 --> 04:26.106
and if you feel better,
maybe we meet later?

04:26.106 --> 04:29.389
‐Perfect. I may have to hop off
for a few minutes

04:29.389 --> 04:31.552
once the painkillers kick in.

04:31.552 --> 04:33.794
‐Mind if I start recording?
‐Go ahead.

04:33.794 --> 04:36.076
[ Watch dings ]

04:36.076 --> 04:39.760
‐All right.
We are on the record now.

04:39.760 --> 04:43.764
‐Well, let's start with the
MAV malfunction straightaway ‐‐

04:43.764 --> 04:47.287
what we think happened,
and how we plan to tackle it.

04:47.287 --> 04:48.769
Um, there have always b‐‐
‐We'll get to the MAV.

04:48.769 --> 04:51.091
I prefer to ask some questions
first.

04:51.091 --> 04:53.213
Let's start with the beginning,
before VISTA.

04:53.213 --> 04:55.455
You made your seed money
through Purifair.

04:55.455 --> 04:57.017
‐Terrible name.

04:57.017 --> 04:58.779
‐Was that Spano or you?

04:58.779 --> 05:01.542
‐His team did some
data analytics et voilà.

05:01.542 --> 05:05.626
And no, I walked away
without a dime from Spano.

05:05.626 --> 05:07.387
Although I did have
some personal savings,

05:07.387 --> 05:11.391
but...peanuts compared
to what we needed for VISTA.

05:11.391 --> 05:13.994
‐In the Economist interview,
you said that y‐‐

05:13.994 --> 05:16.436
‐Which one? 2026 or '30?

05:16.436 --> 05:18.158
‐The most recent.

05:18.158 --> 05:21.201
‐I said I walked away with
the seeds, not the seed money.

05:21.201 --> 05:24.565
‐You remember your exact quote?

05:24.565 --> 05:26.687
‐Photographic memory.

05:26.687 --> 05:29.169
It's a curse
as much as a blessing.

05:29.169 --> 05:33.493
‐So, by seeds, you meant ‐‐
‐Oh, people, some staff,

05:33.493 --> 05:34.735
important connections.

05:34.735 --> 05:37.377
‐Ah, political connections.

05:37.377 --> 05:42.222
‐The beginning of my career has
been written about ad nauseam.

05:42.222 --> 05:44.344
Should we do
something different?

05:44.344 --> 05:47.948
‐I've been told that
you hate doing press.

05:47.948 --> 05:52.232
‐There are those in my field who
nurture the cult of personality.

05:52.232 --> 05:55.195
That doesn't interest me.

05:55.195 --> 05:57.678
But things like this...

05:57.678 --> 06:04.164
Well, they're part of the job,
so we do what we must do.

06:04.164 --> 06:07.167
‐And I'm just trying
to do my job.

06:07.167 --> 06:09.449
‐Then ask me something
I haven't been asked

06:09.449 --> 06:11.131
a hundred times before.

06:13.534 --> 06:16.617
‐Are you happy?
‐[ Laughs ]

06:16.617 --> 06:19.179
‐Got my first laugh.

06:19.179 --> 06:21.221
‐No, I'm not happy.

06:21.221 --> 06:23.183
‐Why not?

06:23.183 --> 06:26.747
‐Happiness is death
by complacency.

06:28.909 --> 06:30.791
‐That's what you
tell your children?

06:30.791 --> 06:35.836
‐I will leave them to draw
their own conclusions.

06:35.836 --> 06:39.079
‐How would your children
describe you?

06:39.079 --> 06:40.601
[ Phone blips ]

06:40.601 --> 06:43.043
‐Aaron, can I call you back
in a few minutes?

06:43.043 --> 06:45.846
‐Those painkillers are quick.
‐They are.

06:45.846 --> 06:47.768
‐And convenient.

06:47.768 --> 06:49.089
[ Phone blips ]

06:49.089 --> 06:51.732
‐I have another call
I need to take.

06:51.732 --> 06:54.935
‐I'll be here.
‐Thanks. End call.

06:54.935 --> 06:57.618
‐[ Sighs ]

06:57.618 --> 07:00.901
‐Answer. This is Laz.
Are we on a secure line?

07:00.901 --> 07:03.544
‐Yes, I'll connect you to
Commander Hagerty now.

07:05.345 --> 07:07.467
Denise?

07:14.154 --> 07:16.436
Come on.
You should eat something.

07:16.436 --> 07:18.078
‐[ Groans ]

07:18.078 --> 07:20.280
[Mumbles] I'm not hungry.

07:20.280 --> 07:22.162
‐[ Sighs ] Eat anyway.

07:26.446 --> 07:29.009
‐[ Sighs ]

07:34.615 --> 07:36.697
‐Is there anything in here
I should worry about?

07:52.633 --> 07:55.556
‐Does my dad know?

07:55.556 --> 07:58.038
‐Yeah. He's on a plane home now.

08:00.080 --> 08:02.763
[ Sighs ]

08:02.763 --> 08:04.965
I wish I could draw like that.

08:06.967 --> 08:10.410
‐I'm finished.

08:10.410 --> 08:13.293
‐I'll leave it there
in case you want some more.

08:20.661 --> 08:22.743
I'll leave the door open.

08:28.789 --> 08:31.311
‐You were telling me
your thoughts on happiness.

08:31.311 --> 08:33.073
‐Right.

08:33.073 --> 08:37.558
‐It's a clever quote,
but I think there's more to it.

08:37.558 --> 08:39.039
‐I don't think your readers
are interested

08:39.039 --> 08:42.082
in whether I'm happy or not.

08:42.082 --> 08:43.403
‐Are you on the spectrum?

08:45.806 --> 08:48.128
‐[ Sighs, chuckles ]

08:48.128 --> 08:50.531
Which one? There are so many.

08:50.531 --> 08:53.574
‐It's been speculated
in other articles.

08:53.574 --> 08:56.697
‐Standing on the shoulders
of dwarves again.

08:56.697 --> 09:00.020
‐I'm not speculating.
I'm asking.

09:00.020 --> 09:01.862
‐Diagnosed, no.

09:01.862 --> 09:04.545
And a‐anyway,
what does it matter?

09:04.545 --> 09:06.747
‐Self‐awareness.

09:06.747 --> 09:09.149
‐I am quite self‐aware.

09:09.149 --> 09:12.553
I mean,
sometimes I wish I wasn't.

09:12.553 --> 09:14.635
‐How do you mean?

09:14.635 --> 09:18.559
‐Do you ever feel imprisoned?

09:18.559 --> 09:21.562
‐By what?
‐You‐‐ Your own thoughts.

09:21.562 --> 09:24.404
Y‐Your thoughts. I‐Imprisoned
is maybe not the right word.

09:24.404 --> 09:26.406
Um...

09:26.406 --> 09:31.051
Um...overwhelmed.

09:31.051 --> 09:34.294
‐Sometimes...but probably not
in the same way.

09:34.294 --> 09:36.056
I don't have the mind you do.

09:36.056 --> 09:38.378
‐Well, you're lucky.
‐I think a lot of people

09:38.378 --> 09:39.900
would kill to have your mind.

09:39.900 --> 09:43.343
‐Flattery won't soften me.
Let's skip that.

09:43.343 --> 09:45.065
‐You softened already.

09:45.065 --> 09:47.427
‐Did I?
‐Show me another article

09:47.427 --> 09:51.071
where you've talked about
being overwhelmed.

09:51.071 --> 09:53.273
Why did you request me?

09:53.273 --> 09:55.155
‐Your editor told you.

09:55.155 --> 09:58.038
‐She showed me the e‐mail.

09:58.038 --> 09:59.880
‐Curiosity, I suppose.

09:59.880 --> 10:03.203
‐I don't buy that.
Here's what I think.

10:03.203 --> 10:07.407
That my reporting has been
critical of the Mars program,

10:07.407 --> 10:09.730
and you haven't given
a major interview

10:09.730 --> 10:12.613
since the explosion, and the
clicks will go through the roof.

10:12.613 --> 10:15.656
And if you can convince me,
a skeptic,

10:15.656 --> 10:17.858
then you will have
public opinion on your side

10:17.858 --> 10:22.022
in case the MAV fix fails.

10:22.022 --> 10:25.305
I also don't buy
your back gave out.

10:25.305 --> 10:27.788
‐Why would I lie about that?
‐You tell me.

10:29.790 --> 10:32.152
‐Yes, I wanted to discuss
the MAV.

10:32.152 --> 10:34.555
That is why I raised it
at the beginning.

10:34.555 --> 10:36.436
In terms of the press,

10:36.436 --> 10:38.799
I didn't give an interview
since the launch

10:38.799 --> 10:41.361
because I thought it was my job
to focus on the work,

10:41.361 --> 10:42.843
not to draw attention
to the things that ‐‐

10:42.843 --> 10:45.165
‐You can retreat
to your talking points,

10:45.165 --> 10:47.648
but that's not
how you win me over.

10:52.412 --> 10:54.655
‐Some people prefer to speak
on the phone

10:54.655 --> 10:59.059
where they can't be seen,
where they can be less...

10:59.059 --> 11:02.102
self‐aware, less self‐conscious.

11:03.984 --> 11:07.668
‐Where they can be
more in control.

11:07.668 --> 11:11.872
‐We have one more shot
at this mission,

11:11.872 --> 11:14.955
and it's important that we show
the world it's in good hands.

11:14.955 --> 11:16.877
‐Your hands.
‐Thousands of people's hands

11:16.877 --> 11:19.680
working day and night to make
sure that it's a success.

11:19.680 --> 11:22.402
‐You could've said the same
about the first launch,

11:22.402 --> 11:26.567
and now you have a major asset
on Mars that isn't working.

11:28.689 --> 11:31.171
‐I'm confident the MAV
will be fully functioning

11:31.171 --> 11:32.573
by the time we launch.

11:32.573 --> 11:35.455
‐Confidence is an attitude,
not a fact.

11:37.538 --> 11:40.541
‐You want me to prove it.
‐That would be nice.

11:50.190 --> 11:51.632
‐Sleep?
‐Normal.

11:51.632 --> 11:53.914
‐Appetite?
‐Normal.

11:53.914 --> 11:55.716
‐Dreams?
‐None.

11:55.716 --> 11:58.238
‐You're not being
entirely honest.

11:58.238 --> 12:00.240
‐Sorry.

12:00.240 --> 12:02.362
‐I don't remember my dreams.

12:02.362 --> 12:05.285
‐You're not being
entirely honest.

12:05.285 --> 12:08.969
‐It's so weird.
‐It's just a beta version.

12:08.969 --> 12:10.731
‐How does he know you're lying?

12:10.731 --> 12:15.295
‐He uses facial cues,
uh...pulse, body temperature.

12:15.295 --> 12:17.177
‐Hmm.

12:17.177 --> 12:20.140
‐Want to give it a try?
‐Oh. I don't know.

12:20.140 --> 12:22.983
‐Yeah. Come on. Go ahead. Yeah.

12:22.983 --> 12:24.304
‐Okay.

12:26.386 --> 12:29.790
‐Matteo, new subject. Begin.

12:29.790 --> 12:31.872
‐I'm Matteo. What's your name?

12:31.872 --> 12:34.074
‐Mm! Feels like our first date.

12:34.074 --> 12:37.638
‐Just tell him your name.
‐I'm Camila Rodriguez.

12:37.638 --> 12:39.279
‐Hello, Camila.
‐[ Chuckles ]

12:39.279 --> 12:40.761
‐What do you want to talk about?

12:44.044 --> 12:50.170
‐So, this is, like, if something
happened to you, right?

12:50.170 --> 12:53.093
‐Or I'm not in the Hab
or I'm asleep.

12:53.093 --> 12:55.856
People respond better when
they have a face to look at.

12:55.856 --> 12:58.819
‐But isn't that messed up?
Like, if you're...

13:01.141 --> 13:03.904
If...

13:03.904 --> 13:09.189
you're dead, then they're
just staring at your ghost.

13:09.189 --> 13:19.199
♪♪

13:19.199 --> 13:29.209
♪♪

13:29.209 --> 13:39.219
♪♪

13:39.219 --> 13:44.825
♪♪

13:44.825 --> 13:46.426
‐All right, let's depressurize.

13:46.426 --> 13:49.189
‐Roger.

13:49.189 --> 13:51.632
Go for depress.

13:51.632 --> 13:54.434
[ Beeping ]

13:54.434 --> 13:57.077
[ Air hissing ]

13:57.077 --> 14:00.961
‐I think it's a mistake
to show him.

14:00.961 --> 14:02.683
‐Laz wants to roll the dice.

14:02.683 --> 14:05.726
‐Did she tell him we've only got
a 40% success rate?

14:05.726 --> 14:08.168
‐It's 42.8%.

14:08.168 --> 14:10.250
And who's got to do
the song and dance?

14:10.250 --> 14:13.053
‐The Head Engineer.

14:13.053 --> 14:15.415
‐You're an engineer
and an astronaut.

14:15.415 --> 14:17.578
‐Okay, rock, paper, scissors.

14:17.578 --> 14:19.179
‐[ Chuckles ] Oh, God, no.

14:19.179 --> 14:21.381
‐You've got a statistically
better chance at winning

14:21.381 --> 14:23.063
than getting this test to work.

14:23.063 --> 14:25.666
‐It's 33%. Isn't that
six different options ‐‐

14:25.666 --> 14:28.148
‐Okay, well, you've got
a 67% chance of not losing.

14:28.148 --> 14:30.150
‐But, actually, the draw's
an automatic redo.

14:30.150 --> 14:31.792
Statistically, it would be ‐‐

14:31.792 --> 14:34.354
‐Okay, let's just do it.
Come on.

14:34.354 --> 14:37.037
‐All right, fine.
‐All right.

14:37.037 --> 14:38.358
One, two ‐‐
‐Wait.

14:38.358 --> 14:40.000
It's after three, correct?

14:40.000 --> 14:41.281
‐On.
‐On?

14:41.281 --> 14:44.164
‐Yeah.
‐All right, fine.

14:44.164 --> 14:46.967
‐One, two, three. Damn it.
‐[ Chuckles ]

14:46.967 --> 14:48.408
‐Okay, two out of three.

14:48.408 --> 14:51.692
‐No way. Enjoy.

14:51.692 --> 14:54.374
‐The rover should arrive at base
camp in approximately 10 weeks.

14:54.374 --> 14:56.937
We'll use its drill to get into
the insulation on the cord

14:56.937 --> 14:58.178
to the mobile power plant.

14:58.178 --> 14:59.780
Zoom in to the reactor.

14:59.780 --> 15:02.663
The drill closes the circuit,
the MAV loses power.

15:02.663 --> 15:04.985
That triggers
an automatic reboot of the CPU.

15:04.985 --> 15:07.227
‐I'm not a tech guy.
‐Let's say you have

15:07.227 --> 15:09.149
a coffee maker
that isn't working,

15:09.149 --> 15:11.672
and you don't know
if it's making coffee or not,

15:11.672 --> 15:13.393
no matter how many
voice commands you give it.

15:13.393 --> 15:15.996
‐The coffee is fuel.
‐Yes, liquid oxygen.

15:15.996 --> 15:17.838
‐Okay.
‐But if you pull the plug

15:17.838 --> 15:20.120
and plug it back in, maybe it
starts talking to you again.

15:20.120 --> 15:22.442
‐The coffee here is shit,
by the way.

15:22.442 --> 15:24.805
‐[ Chuckles ] Budget cuts.
‐[ Chuckles ]

15:24.805 --> 15:27.207
‐Can you get closer
on the power cord?

15:27.207 --> 15:28.969
So, that is our plug.

15:28.969 --> 15:31.612
But instead of unplugging it,
we're shorting it.

15:31.612 --> 15:33.213
Now pull up the simulation.

15:33.213 --> 15:35.135
‐You said "maybe."
You're not certain it'll work.

15:35.135 --> 15:37.698
‐We're still running tests.
You'll see one today.

15:37.698 --> 15:40.220
The key is to have
the drill bit vaporize

15:40.220 --> 15:42.262
the instant it shorts
the circuit.

15:42.262 --> 15:45.105
Otherwise, too much current
loops back on the reactor.

15:45.105 --> 15:47.107
Bad news bears.

15:47.107 --> 15:48.669
‐How bad?

15:48.669 --> 15:50.751
‐[ Imitates explosion ]
That's worst‐case.

15:50.751 --> 15:53.634
Uh, but we do have
a manual‐fix option as a backup.

15:53.634 --> 15:55.235
‐Fix it up there?
‐And we have MAV2

15:55.235 --> 15:56.797
going with us.
There it is.

15:56.797 --> 15:59.319
‐But that means you're launching
with one broken MAV

15:59.319 --> 16:02.082
on the surface,
and the one you're sending,

16:02.082 --> 16:04.565
if that malfunctions
or crashes or...

16:04.565 --> 16:05.686
‐The chances of coming back

16:05.686 --> 16:07.287
are greatly reduced.
‐Greatly.

16:07.287 --> 16:09.089
‐Yes.
‐What are the odds?

16:09.089 --> 16:11.051
‐It's tough to put
exact numbers on it.

16:11.051 --> 16:13.734
‐Coin flip? Better? Worse?

16:13.734 --> 16:16.016
‐They wouldn't let us launch
if it was worse,

16:16.016 --> 16:18.498
but it's not much
on the side of better.

16:19.580 --> 16:21.341
‐[ Chuckles ]

16:21.341 --> 16:22.663
How does that make you feel?

16:22.663 --> 16:26.026
Putting your lives
at that much risk?

16:26.026 --> 16:28.228
‐We don't spend a lot of time
thinking about it.

16:28.228 --> 16:31.431
‐What about your family?

16:31.431 --> 16:33.914
‐All our families know
what we signed up for.

16:37.157 --> 16:38.719
‐[ Sighs ]

16:38.719 --> 16:46.046
♪♪

16:46.046 --> 16:53.293
♪♪

16:53.293 --> 17:00.581
♪♪

17:00.581 --> 17:08.268
♪♪

17:08.268 --> 17:11.592
[ Door opens, closes ]

17:11.592 --> 17:17.197
♪♪

17:17.197 --> 17:19.079
‐Hey.

17:19.079 --> 17:20.681
‐She in her room?
‐Yeah.

17:20.681 --> 17:23.604
She had a bite to eat,
and then she went back to sleep.

17:23.604 --> 17:30.651
♪♪

17:41.662 --> 17:43.704
‐Thank you for this.

17:48.749 --> 17:51.952
Flaring up?
‐Oh, it just started. It's fine.

18:00.440 --> 18:02.322
We need a plan.

18:02.322 --> 18:04.845
It's on me, I took the risk,

18:04.845 --> 18:06.807
but I can't have you leaving.
Not again.

18:09.409 --> 18:11.491
‐I told you
it wouldn't be predictable.

18:11.491 --> 18:13.574
‐I know.

18:13.574 --> 18:15.335
But if the last facility
didn't work,

18:15.335 --> 18:18.018
then let's try a new one,
or home care.

18:18.018 --> 18:19.379
Do you think
she'd be open to that?

18:19.379 --> 18:21.622
‐I haven't even spoken
to her yet.

18:34.835 --> 18:37.918
‐Tom.

18:37.918 --> 18:41.441
‐I appreciate you
looking out for her,

18:41.441 --> 18:43.644
but I think you should go.

18:45.886 --> 18:47.928
‐I need to be part
of this discussion.

18:47.928 --> 18:50.731
‐No, actually, you don't need
to be part of this discussion.

18:50.731 --> 18:52.452
This is between
my daughter and I.

18:52.452 --> 18:54.975
This is family business.
‐Now it's my business, too,

18:54.975 --> 18:56.857
because you're our commander.

18:56.857 --> 18:59.900
‐[ Sighs ]

18:59.900 --> 19:03.544
Hey.

19:03.544 --> 19:06.306
You okay?

19:06.306 --> 19:09.269
‐Yeah, just...gonna go
take a shower.

19:16.476 --> 19:18.719
[ Door opens, closes ]

19:18.719 --> 19:22.242
[ Watch beeping ]

19:22.242 --> 19:23.884
‐[ Sighs ]

19:23.884 --> 19:25.285
‐This is Laz.

19:25.285 --> 19:28.288
‐We're ready.
Want me to sync you now?

19:28.288 --> 19:30.651
‐Do it without me and then
call me after. End call.

19:30.651 --> 19:32.292
[ Phone blips ]

19:32.292 --> 19:34.334
‐That's the drill test...

19:37.538 --> 19:38.939
...for the Times piece.

19:44.304 --> 19:46.346
‐You need a heat pack?
‐No.

19:46.346 --> 19:48.428
I got some meds in my bag.

19:59.279 --> 20:01.842
I could've sworn...

20:01.842 --> 20:03.443
Hmm.

20:07.648 --> 20:11.411
‐Were you only in the kitchen
and out here with your bag?

20:14.615 --> 20:16.016
‐Yeah.

20:16.016 --> 20:17.978
And Denise's room, but...

20:20.140 --> 20:22.983
‐What kind of meds? Painkillers?

20:22.983 --> 20:24.304
‐Yeah.

20:24.304 --> 20:31.271
♪♪

20:31.271 --> 20:33.353
‐Denise?!
[ Water running ]

20:33.353 --> 20:35.516
Denise, open the door, baby!
‐What?!

20:35.516 --> 20:39.640
‐Open the door. Open it!
Come on! Open the door for me!

20:39.640 --> 20:41.281
[ Banging on door ]

20:41.281 --> 20:43.243
You have that purse
in there with you?!

20:43.243 --> 20:45.926
‐Tom! I found it.

20:45.926 --> 20:51.652
♪♪

20:51.652 --> 20:53.453
[ Water shuts off ]

20:53.453 --> 21:03.463
♪♪

21:03.463 --> 21:08.428
♪♪

21:19.279 --> 21:20.801
[ Door locks ]

21:20.801 --> 21:24.605
‐Okay, let's lower it.

21:24.605 --> 21:27.888
[ Whirring ]

21:33.213 --> 21:34.735
‐We've made contact.

21:39.179 --> 21:40.861
‐What am I looking for?

21:40.861 --> 21:42.863
‐A flash when the bit vaporizes.

21:42.863 --> 21:44.945
[ Whirring continues ]

21:58.238 --> 22:00.000
‐Okay, power down.

22:00.000 --> 22:01.361
‐It didn't work.

22:01.361 --> 22:03.844
‐No.
‐Is that a fluke or...

22:03.844 --> 22:05.445
‐We haven't achieved
consistency yet.

22:05.445 --> 22:08.609
‐How inconsistent are you?
‐This is early stages.

22:08.609 --> 22:11.491
There's plenty of room
for improvement.

22:11.491 --> 22:13.013
‐Yeah.

22:18.899 --> 22:20.581
[ Door opens ]

22:31.111 --> 22:33.353
‐Are you ready to talk?

22:38.478 --> 22:40.681
I can just listen if you want.

23:04.945 --> 23:06.867
‐I don't know what to say.

23:11.311 --> 23:13.433
‐What happened?

23:13.433 --> 23:16.156
‐I don't really know
how I ended up there.

23:16.156 --> 23:20.320
I wasn't even high yet.
I just...

23:20.320 --> 23:23.203
It was the painting.

23:23.203 --> 23:26.126
I finished the one of Mom,
and I just...

23:26.126 --> 23:32.092
♪♪

23:32.092 --> 23:34.895
‐Oh, my God.

23:34.895 --> 23:36.817
‐Everybody, out!

23:36.817 --> 23:38.939
Let's go!
Everybody out of there.

23:38.939 --> 23:40.661
Are you okay?

23:40.661 --> 23:42.422
Can you tell me what you took?

23:42.422 --> 23:45.105
♪♪

23:45.105 --> 23:46.547
We need an EMT over here.

23:46.547 --> 23:48.348
‐No! No!

23:48.348 --> 23:50.511
No! No! No!

23:52.513 --> 23:54.795
I fought him when he tried
to pull me out.

23:54.795 --> 23:56.957
Then...

23:56.957 --> 24:00.040
Then I was in the hospital
and then jail.

24:04.965 --> 24:07.528
‐[ Sighs ]

24:10.050 --> 24:13.053
And why did you call Laz
instead of me?

24:13.053 --> 24:17.097
‐You were out of town.
She wasn't.

24:17.097 --> 24:19.219
And...

24:19.219 --> 24:21.101
I was afraid.

24:21.101 --> 24:23.263
‐Of what?

24:23.263 --> 24:25.986
‐[ Voice breaking ]
Of fucking everything up again.

24:34.995 --> 24:38.198
‐When...

24:38.198 --> 24:40.040
you OD'd back in New York ‐‐

24:40.040 --> 24:42.242
‐I didn't OD this time.

24:45.165 --> 24:47.247
‐But you could've.

24:47.247 --> 24:50.531
You could've.

24:50.531 --> 24:53.934
That's all I think about.

24:53.934 --> 24:57.538
I remember you...

24:57.538 --> 24:59.099
hooked up to all those machines,

24:59.099 --> 25:01.261
your skin so pale,

25:01.261 --> 25:04.344
your heartbeat s‐‐

25:04.344 --> 25:05.986
skipping.

25:05.986 --> 25:11.191
Any m‐‐ moment, it could stop.

25:11.191 --> 25:13.634
And that's what scares me.

25:13.634 --> 25:16.797
That I'm gonna get that call

25:16.797 --> 25:18.559
that you're gone.

25:22.763 --> 25:27.447
[ Sighs ]

25:27.447 --> 25:31.131
‐Mom and I felt that.

25:31.131 --> 25:32.773
When you were up there.

25:44.625 --> 25:47.427
‐What do we do?

25:47.427 --> 25:49.189
How do we fix this?

25:54.795 --> 25:56.797
‐We're working on
our success rate.

25:56.797 --> 25:59.199
‐You said you were confident.
‐I am confident.

25:59.199 --> 26:02.202
We've still got time.
‐What I saw is a failed test.

26:02.202 --> 26:05.485
The engineers tell me you're not
anywhere close to consistency,

26:05.485 --> 26:08.569
and if you fail, you're putting
lives at increased risk.

26:08.569 --> 26:10.651
That's your version
of confidence?

26:12.693 --> 26:16.857
‐I'm confident in what
we're capable of achieving.

26:16.857 --> 26:19.299
No one thought...

26:19.299 --> 26:22.823
we'd raise the venture capital.
We did.

26:22.823 --> 26:26.026
No one thought we'd get
NASA on board. We did.

26:26.026 --> 26:27.708
No one thought we'd have
a transit vehicle

26:27.708 --> 26:29.870
prototype by 2026.
We did.

26:29.870 --> 26:33.033
Or that we'd get it built
within two years. We did.

26:33.033 --> 26:38.358
Every asset, every satellite,
dozens of launches.

26:38.358 --> 26:42.442
I had the confidence we could.
And I was right.

26:42.442 --> 26:46.406
‐70 years, NASA's had, what,
a 4% fatality rate?

26:46.406 --> 26:48.488
‐You can't hold Mars
to the same standard.

26:48.488 --> 26:50.531
‐When it's people lives
I sure as hell can.

26:50.531 --> 26:52.533
‐You keep focusing
on the explosion

26:52.533 --> 26:54.695
rather than all the success
before it.

26:54.695 --> 26:57.658
‐And you keep deflecting.
‐Quite the opposite.

26:57.658 --> 27:01.782
Yes. People died.

27:01.782 --> 27:04.825
And people will die.

27:04.825 --> 27:08.989
Any time people venture into
the unknown, there is a cost.

27:08.989 --> 27:13.153
Space has never been safe.
No frontier is safe.

27:13.153 --> 27:14.755
Quote me ‐‐

27:14.755 --> 27:18.559
When it comes to Mars,
we must get used to death.

27:18.559 --> 27:23.363
I believe it's worth
the lives we lose.

27:23.363 --> 27:28.048
‐The five astronauts you lost ‐‐
doesn't that eat at you?

27:28.048 --> 27:30.010
Doesn't that give you pause?

27:30.010 --> 27:34.775
‐Y‐You're asking me to weigh
my entire life's work

27:34.775 --> 27:36.136
against the loss of life.

27:36.136 --> 27:38.098
It's an impossible question.

27:38.098 --> 27:40.661
‐But it's the question.

27:40.661 --> 27:42.382
It's the question
that never goes away.

27:42.382 --> 27:44.304
It's their lives, not yours.

27:44.304 --> 27:46.587
‐You don't understand.

27:46.587 --> 27:50.350
Not finishing
what I was meant to do...

27:50.350 --> 27:53.994
that's worse than death.

27:53.994 --> 27:56.917
I can't explain it.
‐If you can't explain it to me,

27:56.917 --> 27:58.799
good luck
with the rest of the world.

28:01.201 --> 28:03.363
‐I want you to watch
another test.

28:05.806 --> 28:09.369
I'll get Eitan
to double the voltage.

28:09.369 --> 28:13.934
I'll rig it so that you can see
how it's supposed to work.

28:13.934 --> 28:16.336
‐That doesn't prove anything.

28:16.336 --> 28:18.699
‐All the people
who have doubted me ‐‐

28:18.699 --> 28:22.783
professors, investors,
politicians, journalists ‐‐

28:22.783 --> 28:26.346
they all said the same thing ‐‐
"I'll believe it when I see it."

28:26.346 --> 28:31.592
But that's backwards.
Belief comes first.

28:31.592 --> 28:34.635
Only then can you see it.
‐I don't report fictions.

28:34.635 --> 28:37.357
‐I'm asking you
to use your imagination.

28:37.357 --> 28:47.367
♪♪

28:47.367 --> 28:51.892
♪♪

28:56.857 --> 29:00.380
‐So, I'll quit.

29:00.380 --> 29:02.783
‐No.
I don't want to hold you back.

29:02.783 --> 29:05.786
‐You're more important.
‐I'm not.

29:10.991 --> 29:13.954
‐I know you think that your mom,
that I ‐‐

29:13.954 --> 29:16.156
‐Look, I didn't mean that.

29:16.156 --> 29:18.799
‐[ Voice breaking ] You might be
right. I just can't change it.

29:21.201 --> 29:22.803
And I don't want
to lose you, too.

29:22.803 --> 29:24.645
‐I don't want to lose you,
either.

29:24.645 --> 29:26.166
‐So, I'll stay.

29:26.166 --> 29:28.689
‐You'd hate me.

29:28.689 --> 29:30.450
And I'd hate myself.

29:54.474 --> 29:56.877
[ Water running ]

30:16.456 --> 30:18.098
‐Denise?

30:18.098 --> 30:20.821
We need a plan.

30:20.821 --> 30:24.184
I'm not trying
to be insensitive, but we do.

30:28.028 --> 30:30.831
‐Yeah.

30:30.831 --> 30:32.192
I'll go to Myk's.

30:32.192 --> 30:36.356
‐Um, that's not
a very good idea.

30:36.356 --> 30:40.360
‐She's my sponsor.
‐And she's an addict.

30:40.360 --> 30:41.882
‐I can't stay here anymore.

30:41.882 --> 30:43.564
‐All right, then we'll just

30:43.564 --> 30:44.885
find something else,
we'll rent something.

30:44.885 --> 30:46.086
We'll get out of here
for a while,

30:46.086 --> 30:47.447
do whatever we have to do.
‐No.

30:47.447 --> 30:49.169
No, no, no, no.
I want to go to Myk's.

30:49.169 --> 30:51.411
‐Denise, what was it
about the last program?

30:51.411 --> 30:52.492
What didn't you like about it?
‐No, no, no.

30:52.492 --> 30:54.134
I‐I'm not going to rehab again.

30:54.134 --> 30:55.536
‐Maybe it was
just the wrong fit.

30:55.536 --> 30:58.018
‐You guys are not going
to ship me out!

30:58.018 --> 31:00.260
‐No, don't you ‐‐ Don't!

31:00.260 --> 31:04.024
No. No. I'm going.

31:04.024 --> 31:05.385
‐You're not in a position

31:05.385 --> 31:07.027
to make very good decisions
right now.

31:07.027 --> 31:09.389
‐I'll jump off the fucking
balcony if I have to!

31:09.389 --> 31:11.912
‐No, that you won't do.
Sit down!

31:11.912 --> 31:14.394
‐Tom.

31:14.394 --> 31:16.557
‐This is ‐‐ This is my daughter.

31:19.119 --> 31:21.041
‐Why won't you just let me go?

31:21.041 --> 31:22.603
You know,
it would be so much easier

31:22.603 --> 31:24.084
for both of you,
for everybody ‐‐

31:24.084 --> 31:26.086
‐I can't do ‐‐ I can't do that!
Okay?

31:26.086 --> 31:27.407
‐Then I never should've
come back.

31:27.407 --> 31:29.209
‐And what ‐‐
what were you gonna do?

31:29.209 --> 31:31.732
Just be out on the street?
‐There's nothing for me here!

31:31.732 --> 31:34.575
‐There's me! There's me!

31:34.575 --> 31:37.257
‐No, we tried that,
and it doesn't work!

31:37.257 --> 31:39.259
‐You know, I can't help it,
but I hate your mother.

31:39.259 --> 31:41.141
I hate your mother
for putting us in this. I ‐‐

31:41.141 --> 31:42.983
‐Don't you dare blame her!

31:42.983 --> 31:46.426
‐She left! I haven't!
I'm still here!

31:48.549 --> 31:50.110
‐You know what?
She was there for me more

31:50.110 --> 31:52.432
than you will ever be! Ever!

31:52.432 --> 31:55.115
‐All right, you know what?
All right, fine. Fine.

31:55.115 --> 31:56.957
Walk out the door
in your bare feet.

31:56.957 --> 32:00.000
Go drown yourself in the same
goddamn river she did. Go.

32:00.000 --> 32:01.722
‐That's enough!
‐No, no, I didn't mean it.

32:01.722 --> 32:03.163
‐No! Get off!
‐I didn't mean it. I'm sorry.

32:03.163 --> 32:05.365
Fuck. Fuck!

32:05.365 --> 32:07.848
I'm sorry.

32:07.848 --> 32:09.369
‐Denise.

32:09.369 --> 32:12.092
Denise, this is what I want.

32:12.092 --> 32:15.455
I want you to come home with me.
I have a guesthouse.

32:15.455 --> 32:17.257
You'll have your own space,
okay?

32:17.257 --> 32:19.820
Just for a few days.
Just breathe.

32:19.820 --> 32:22.703
We don't have to figure
everything out right now.

32:22.703 --> 32:26.026
Will you do that?
Okay, get your stuff.

32:26.026 --> 32:35.275
♪♪

32:35.275 --> 32:44.525
♪♪

32:44.525 --> 32:53.734
♪♪

32:53.734 --> 33:03.023
♪♪

33:03.023 --> 33:12.072
♪♪

33:12.072 --> 33:14.154
‐[ Sighs ]

33:23.604 --> 33:33.373
♪♪

33:33.373 --> 33:43.143
♪♪

33:43.143 --> 33:44.905
‐Drill at speed.

33:44.905 --> 33:46.667
‐Okay, lower the arm.

33:46.667 --> 33:50.551
♪♪

33:50.551 --> 33:53.193
‐We've made contact.

33:53.193 --> 33:57.397
‐Rub two sticks together
long enough...

33:57.397 --> 34:00.601
fast enough...

34:00.601 --> 34:02.523
your palms will blister.

34:02.523 --> 34:05.285
♪♪

34:05.285 --> 34:07.568
You'll rub the skin right off.

34:07.568 --> 34:10.931
Your jaw will clench
from the pain.

34:10.931 --> 34:14.414
[ Wind howling ]

34:14.414 --> 34:17.417
You'll fail,
and you'll fail again.

34:17.417 --> 34:19.419
[ Birds cawing ]

34:19.419 --> 34:24.064
♪♪

34:24.064 --> 34:25.506
But then...

34:25.506 --> 34:31.872
♪♪

34:31.872 --> 34:35.355
...where there was darkness,

34:35.355 --> 34:36.797
there's light.

34:36.797 --> 34:40.521
♪♪

34:40.521 --> 34:42.362
Where there was cold...

34:42.362 --> 34:47.608
♪♪

34:47.608 --> 34:49.249
...there's warmth.

34:49.249 --> 34:53.934
♪♪

34:53.934 --> 34:56.336
You can see every corner
of the cave.

34:56.336 --> 34:59.940
♪♪

34:59.940 --> 35:01.942
You can walk into the night

35:01.942 --> 35:05.746
even without the moon or stars
to guide you.

35:05.746 --> 35:07.708
♪♪

35:07.708 --> 35:11.992
But to get there,
you had to believe.

35:11.992 --> 35:16.957
♪♪

35:16.957 --> 35:19.520
You had to believe there was
fire within the dead wood

35:19.520 --> 35:21.522
that made your fingers bleed.

35:21.522 --> 35:27.928
♪♪

35:27.928 --> 35:31.251
No, it wasn't God
that lit the way.

35:35.656 --> 35:38.218
It was your own two hands.

35:38.218 --> 35:43.023
♪♪

35:43.023 --> 35:44.785
‐It's beautiful.

35:44.785 --> 35:48.188
♪♪

35:48.188 --> 35:51.071
‐Why don't you
come up to the house?

35:51.071 --> 35:52.593
‐[ Chuckles ]

35:52.593 --> 35:56.156
‐I'll get Jason to make
the arrangements.

35:56.156 --> 35:57.718
End call.

36:04.885 --> 36:07.528
You may want to stay put
in the guesthouse

36:07.528 --> 36:09.930
when the reporter comes.

36:09.930 --> 36:12.052
If that's all right with you.

36:12.052 --> 36:13.534
‐Okay.

36:13.534 --> 36:23.544
♪♪

36:23.544 --> 36:33.554
♪♪

36:33.554 --> 36:43.564
♪♪

36:43.564 --> 36:53.574
♪♪

36:53.574 --> 37:03.584
♪♪

37:03.584 --> 37:13.594
♪♪

37:13.594 --> 37:23.604
♪♪

37:23.604 --> 37:33.614
♪♪

37:33.614 --> 37:43.624
♪♪

37:43.624 --> 37:53.634
♪♪

37:53.634 --> 38:00.841
♪♪

38:00.841 --> 38:03.043
‐The fridge
should be fully stocked,

38:03.043 --> 38:05.045
um, but if you want
anything else,

38:05.045 --> 38:06.687
make a list,
and we can get it for you.

38:06.687 --> 38:08.488
And if you don't feel
like cooking,

38:08.488 --> 38:11.131
the chef will be here from
2:00 till 10:00 p. m. every day.

38:11.131 --> 38:16.096
There's a housekeeper at midday
to do a tidy and take laundry.

38:16.096 --> 38:19.179
Okay?

38:19.179 --> 38:21.942
I'll let you get settled, then.

38:27.748 --> 38:37.558
♪♪

38:37.558 --> 38:47.367
♪♪

38:47.367 --> 38:49.530
‐What are you most afraid of?

38:49.530 --> 38:53.894
♪♪

38:53.894 --> 38:57.137
‐I'm supposed to say
"losing another crew."

38:57.137 --> 39:00.741
‐What are you
not supposed to say?

39:00.741 --> 39:02.743
‐"Being willing to lose
another crew."

39:02.743 --> 39:03.984
[ Camera shutter clicks ]

39:03.984 --> 39:06.587
♪♪

39:06.587 --> 39:09.590
Why don't you just transcribe
the recording?

39:09.590 --> 39:13.634
‐Writing it longhand helps
bake things into my brain.

39:13.634 --> 39:16.557
‐How 20th century of you.

39:16.557 --> 39:18.919
‐Not all innovation is progress.

39:22.442 --> 39:25.485
‐I suppose if you write down
everything I've said today,

39:25.485 --> 39:28.248
I won't come off very well.

39:28.248 --> 39:30.611
‐Better than if you'd
kept your guard up.

39:30.611 --> 39:34.254
People respond to honesty.
But you know that.

39:34.254 --> 39:37.538
‐Do I?
‐It's a strategy, too.

39:37.538 --> 39:39.780
‐You must think
I'm very calculated.

39:39.780 --> 39:44.424
‐I think you have to be.

39:44.424 --> 39:45.986
‐Oh, could I have a tissue?

39:53.273 --> 39:55.395
‐I suppose you think this
is a case in point.

39:55.395 --> 39:57.558
She wiped all her makeup off

39:57.558 --> 39:59.800
so she doesn't look glamorous
for the photo shoot.

39:59.800 --> 40:03.483
‐No, I've only got 3,000 words.
‐[ Chuckles ]

40:03.483 --> 40:05.085
‐We're ready when you are,
Ms. Ingram.

40:05.085 --> 40:06.486
‐Okay.

40:08.649 --> 40:10.651
[ Grunts ]

40:10.651 --> 40:13.293
Could you give me a hand?
‐Yeah. Here.

40:18.699 --> 40:20.541
‐I promise to make this quick.

40:20.541 --> 40:23.223
‐Well, you take the time you
need. You have a job to do.

40:23.223 --> 40:26.426
‐Okay. We're just gonna run
some, uh, test shots,

40:26.426 --> 40:30.951
so you might want to close your
eyes while we run the flash.

40:30.951 --> 40:33.554
‐Aaron.
‐Yeah?

40:33.554 --> 40:35.315
‐You know at the beginning
when you asked me

40:35.315 --> 40:38.999
about the seed money?
‐Yes.

40:38.999 --> 40:40.601
‐It was my sister.

40:40.601 --> 40:43.203
‐The model?
